=Bonami |first1=Olivier |last2=Godard |first2=Dani\u00e8le |title=On the Syntax of Direct Quotation in French |url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00751080/document |website=HAL |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Quotations are also used to present well-known statement parts that are explicitly attributed by [[citation]] to their original source; such statements are marked with ([[punctuation|punctuated]] with) [[quotation mark]]s.\n\nQuotations are often used as a literary device to represent someone's point of view. They are also widely used in spoken language when an interlocutor wishes to present a proposition that they have come to know via hearsay.\n\n==Quotations as a literary device==\nA quotation can also refer to the repeated use of units of any other form of expression, especially parts of artistic works: elements of a [[painting]], scenes from a [[film|movie]] or sections from a [[musical composition]].\n\n===Reasons for using quotations as a literary device===\nQuotations are used for a variety of reasons: to illuminate the meaning or to support the arguments of the work in which it is being quoted, to provide direct information about the work being quoted (whether in order to discuss it, positively or negatively), to pay homage to the original work or [[author]], to make the user of the quotation seem well-read, and/or to comply with copyright law.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.elc.edu/english-grammar-lesson-using-quotes/|title=English Grammar Lesson - Using Quotes! - ELC|date=2016-11-16|work=ELC - English Language Center|access-date=2017-10-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Quotations are also commonly printed as a means of inspiration and to invoke philosophical thoughts from the reader. Pragmatically speaking, quotations can also be used as language games (in the Wittgensteinian sense of the term) to manipulate social order and the structure of society.<ref>Capone, A., & Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2014). On indirect reports and language games: Evidence from Persian. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 8(2), 26-42.</ref><ref>Salmani Nodoushan, M. A. (2015). The secret life of slurs from the perspective of reported speech. Rivista Italiana di Filosofia del Linguaggio, 9(2), 92-112.</ref>\n\n===Common quotation sources===\nFamous quotations are frequently collected in books that are sometimes called quotation dictionaries or treasuries.  Of these, ''[[Bartlett's Familiar Quotations]]'', ''[[The Oxford Dictionary of Quotations]]'', ''The [[Columbia University Press|Columbia]] Dictionary of Quotations'', ''[[The Yale Book of Quotations]]'' and ''The [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Book of Proverbs, Maxims, and Famous Phrases'' are considered among the most reliable and comprehensive sources.  Diaries and calendars often include quotations for entertainment or inspirational purposes, and small, dedicated sections in newspapers and weekly magazines\u2014with recent quotations by leading personalities on current topics\u2014have also become commonplace.\n\n===Misquotations===\n{{further|False attribution}}\n{{See also|List of movie misquotes}}\nMany quotations are routinely incorrect or attributed to the wrong authors, and quotations from obscure or unknown writers are often attributed to far more famous writers. Examples of this are [[Winston Churchill]], to whom many political quotations of uncertain origin are attributed, and [[Oscar Wilde]], to whom anonymous humorous quotations are sometimes attributed.<ref>See ''A Book of Misquotations'', edited by Elizabeth Knowles, Oxford University Press, 2006.</ref>\n\nThe ''Star Trek'' catchphrase \"[[Beam me up, Scotty]]\" did not appear in that form in the original series. Other misquotations include \"[[Just the facts, ma'am]]\" (attributed to [[Jack Webb]]'s character of [[Joe Friday]] on ''[[Dragnet (series)|Dragnet]]''), \"Heavy lies the crown\" from Shakespeare's Play [[Henry IV, Part 2]], \"[[Sherlock Holmes#\"Elementary, my dear Watson\"|Elementary, my dear Watson]]\" (attributed to [[Sherlock Holmes]]; it was, however, said in the films ''[[The Adventures of Sherlock Holmes]]'' and ''[[The Return of Sherlock Holmes (1929 film)|The Return of Sherlock Holmes]]''), \"[[Luke, I am your father]]\" (attributed to [[Darth Vader]] in [[Star Wars]]), \"[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Play it again, Sam]]\" (attributed to Ilsa in ''[[Casablanca (film)#Quotations|Casablanca]]''), \"[[Do you feel lucky, punk?]]\" (attributed to [[Dirty Harry (character)|Harry Callahan]] in ''[[Dirty Harry]]'') and \"[[Stinking badges|We don't need no stinkin' badges!]]\" (attributed to Gold Hat in ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'').<ref>The Holmes phrase originated in a radio play. See [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/quotes/signature/elementary.asp \"Elementary, My Dear Watson\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>Webb ''did'' say: \"All we want are the facts ma'am\". See [[Just the facts, ma'am]], [[q:List of misquotations|List of misquotations]] and [http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/tv/dragnet.asp \"Just the Facts\"] at Snopes.com</ref><ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/moments02.html Greatest Film Misquotes - Part 2], Tim Dirks at filmsite.org</ref><ref>{{youtube|nsdZKCh6RsU|We Dont Need No Stinkin Badges!}} although the last of these is spoken by one of the Mexican Bandits that Hedley Lamarr attempts to hire as mercenaries in ''Blazing Saddles''</ref>\n\n==Quotations in spoken discourse==\n===Reasons for using quotations===\n\nQuotations are employed in spoken discourse for many reasons. They are often used by speakers to depict stories and events that have occurred in the past to other interlocutors. The speaker does not necessarily have to have been an original participant in the story or event. Therefore, they can quote something that they did not hear firsthand. Quotations are also used to express thoughts that have never been uttered aloud prior to being quoted. For example: while telling a story, a speaker quotes inner thoughts that they had during a specific situation. Finally, speakers use quotations to propose future dialogue for participants in a situation that may take place in the future. For example: two friends talk about their 10-year high school reunion that will take place in the future. While future dialogue can be proposed for a situation that will likely happen, it can also be based on a situation that will not actually take place. In the latter usage, the proposed dialogue only exists in the conversational context.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sams |first1=Jessie |title=Quoting the unspoken: An analysis of quotations in spoken discourse |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=November 2010 |volume=42 |issue=11 |pages=3147\u20133160 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2010.04.024 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216610001220 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe quoted material is usually not a verbatim replication of an utterance that someone originally said. Instead, quotations in spoken discourse reproduce what a speaker wishes to communicate to their recipients; they demonstrate something that another person said, the manner in which that person said it, and the current speaker\u2019s feelings about what was said.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sams |first1=Jessie |title=Quoting the unspoken: An analysis of quotations in spoken discourse |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=November 2010 |volume=42 |issue=11 |pages=3147\u20133160 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2010.04.024 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216610001220 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clark |first1=Herbert |last2=Gerrig |first2=Richard |title=Quotations as Demonstrations |journal=Language |date=December 1990 |volume=66 |issue=4 |pages=764\u2013805 |doi=10.2307/414729 |url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Quotations-as-Demonstrations.-Clark-Gerrig/54571a1199be1954678338a879189359fab44182 |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Form of quotation===\n\nIn spoken language, there are several ways to present a quotation. For example, the speaker may begin with a lead-in that relates a quotation to the topic currently being discussed, which may be followed by supplementary information on the person to be quoted, and finally the quotation itself.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McArthur |first1=Tom |last2=Lam-McArthur |first2=Jacqueline |last3=Fontaine |first3=Lisa |title=The Oxford Companion to the English Language$ The Oxford Companion to the English Language (2 ed.) |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780191744389 |edition=2nd}}</ref> The quotation is introduced by a quotative marker.\n\n====Quotative markers====\n===== English =====\nIn English, the verb ''\"be like\"'' or ''\"said\"'' are being used as quotatives in American English. <ref> Frederica Barbieri. ''Quotative Use in American English'', Journal of English Linguistics, Vol. 33/No.3, September 2005. p.222. </ref> In conversation, the use of ''\"say\"'' and ''\"be like\"'' are about the same frequency <ref> Frederica Barbieri. ''Quotative Use in American English'', Journal of English Linguistics, Vol. 33/No.3, September 2005. p.240. </ref> ; yet, in more normal situation, for instance office hours between professors and students, will more like to use ''\"say\"'' than ''\"be like\"''. <ref> Frederica Barbieri. ''Quotative Use in American English'', Journal of English Linguistics, Vol. 33/No.3, September 2005. p.242. </ref> \n\nHere are some examples of ''\"be like\"'': <ref> Frederica Barbieri. ''Quotative Use in American English'', Journal of English Linguistics, Vol. 33/No.3, September 2005. p.247. </ref>\n<br>\n\n'''* First person quotative'''\n\n'''I'm''' like \"I thought you were telling me to shut.\"\n'''I'm''' like \"I'm so sorry you had to wait\"\n\n\n===== Japanese =====\nIn Japanese, the quotative marker ''to'' with verbs of saying and thinking, for instance ''iu'' (say) and ''omou'' (think), etc.\nHere are some examples that illustrate this use:<br> \n\nConventions: TOP=Topic Markers AKK=Accusative COM=Complementizer HON=Honorific/ Polite form\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! \u592a\u90ce !! \u306f !! \u6674\u6d77\u3000!! \u3092 !! \u618e\u3093\u3067\u3044\u308b !! \u3068 !! \u8a00\u3063\u305f\u3002<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\"/>\n|-\n| Taro || wa || Harumi || o || nikundeiru || to || itta.\n|-\n| Taro || TOP || Harumi || AKK || nikundeiru || COM || said\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''Taro said that he hated Harumi.''\" lit. \"''that 'I hated Harumi''''\"\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! \u5c71\u7530\u3055\u3093 !! \u306f !! \u4eca\u65e5\u3000!! \u75c5\u6c17 !! \u3060 !! \u3068 !! \u805e\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\"/>\n|-\n| Yamada-san || wa || ky\u00f4 || by\u00f4ki || da || to || kikimashita.\n|-\n| Mr.Yamada || TOP || today || sick || is || COM || heard, +hon\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''I heard that Mr. Yamada is sick today''\" lit. \"that 'He is sick''''\"\n|}\n\nThe pattern of quotative in spoken Japanese is _________x to V where X can be a sentence, a clause or a word. The verb is usually a verb of communication or thought. In spoken Japanese, the use of pronouns and honorific form are commonly seen; yet, honorific form is not an evidence between direct and indirect speech. Thus, Japanese fails to distinguish between direct and indirect speech as shown in the above examples.\n<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\"/>\n\n===Syntax of quotation===\n====Quotative inversion====\n====Nested quotations====\n====Crosslinguisic variations====\n=====Quotative verbs=====\n\n=====Quotative particles=====\nQuotative or hearsay particles are markers equivalent to full verbs with meanings ''say, speak, mention, tell, etc.''\n<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\">{{cite journal |last1=Matsui |first1=Tomoko |last2=Yamamoto |first2=Taeko |title=Developing sensitivity to the sources of information: Early use of the Japanese quotative particles tte and to in mother\u2013child conversation |journal=Journal of Pragmatics |date=2013 |volume=59 |issue= |pages=5-25 |doi=10.1016/j.pragma.2013.06.008 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0378216613001598|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapanese, for example, uses a sentence-final quotative particle ''tte'' verbally to mean \"I heard (quote)\" with some uncertainty. In sentence-medial position, ''tte'' is sometimes regarded along with ''to'' to be either a quotative particle or complementizer meaning \"I heard (quote)\" with less uncertainty and often more knowledge of the origin of the quote.\n\nGloss: QP=Quotative Particle FP=Final Particle\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! \u660e\u65e5 !! \u6674\u308c\u308b !! -\u3063\u3066\u3000<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\" />\n|-\n| Ashita || hareru || ''tte''.\n|-\n| tomorrow || will-be-fine || QP\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''It will be fine tomorrow, I heard.''\"\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! \u660e\u65e5 !! \u6674\u308c\u308b !! -\u3063\u3066/\u3068 !! \u8a00\u3063\u3066\u305f\u3000!!\u3000\u3088\u3000<ref name=\"Matsui and Yamamoto\" />\n|-\n| Ashita || hareru || ''tte''/''to'' || itteta || yo.\n|-\n| tomorrow || will-be-fine || QP || said || FP\n|-\n| colspan=7|\"''(X) said that it would be fine tomorrow.''\"\n|}\n\n=====Quotative evidentials=====\nQuotative evidentials provide knowledge of who or where information originated from in speech. Languages indicate this in various ways such as through additional words and phrases, prosody, gestures, or required endings of verbs. For example, English can express evidentials with optional adverbs, \"Allegedly, Annie pulled the trigger.\" The interlocutor then knows that this is information from a secondary source.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=San Roque |first1=Lila |title=Evidentiality |journal=Annual Review of Anthropology |date=2019 |volume=48 |issue= |pages=353-370 |doi=10.1146/annurev-anthro-102218-011243 |url=https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-anthro-102218-011243|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource portal|Quotations}}\n{{div col}}\n*[[Adage]]\n*[[Aphorism]]\n*[[Block quotation]]\n*[[Epigram]]\n*[[Fallacy of quoting out of context]]\n*[[Saying|Maxim (saying)]]\n*[[Musical quotation]]\n*[[Nested quotation]]\n*[[Proverb]]\n*[[Scare quotes]]\n*[[Sic]]\n*[[Use\u2013mention distinction]]\n*[[Quotation mark]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n<!--===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS   |\n    | NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS.                                              |\n    |                                                                         | \n    |               Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    |  See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.   |\n    |                                                                         | \n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or       |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page.  Or submit your link    |\n    | to the appropriate category at the Open Directory Project (www.dmoz.org)|\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.             |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===============================-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Coulmas p164\">Florian Coulmas (Ed.). ''Direct and Indirect Speech (Trends in Linguistics: Studies and Monographs)'', p.164. {{ISBN|978-3110105995}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Appropriation in the arts|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Quotations| ]]\n[[Category:Communication]]\n", "name_user": "FUNG F", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReasons for using quotations:changed section title to be more specific", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quotation"}
{"title_page": "Shi Zhengli", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese researcher at the Wuhan Institute of Virology}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Shi (surname)|Shi]]}} \n{{Infobox scientist\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| name        = Shi Zhenglii\n| other_names = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|05|26}} \n| birth_place = [[Xixia County]], [[Henan]], China\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|}} or {{Death year and age| }}-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| residence   = \n| fields      = [[Virology]]\n| workplaces  = [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]]<br/> [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] (CAS)\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Wuhan University]]<br/>[[Wuhan Institute of Virology]]<br>[[Montpellier 2 University]]\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| awards      = \n| thesis_title =  <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =  <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =  <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =  <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| signature   =  <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =  <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes   = \n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u77f3|\u6b63|\u4e3d}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u77f3|\u6b63|\u9e97}}\n|p = Sh\u00ed Zh\u00e8ngl\u00ec \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n'''Shi Zhengli''' ({{zh|s=\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d|t=\u77f3\u6b63\u9e97}}; born 26 May 1964) is a Chinese [[virologist]] who has been dubbed \"bat woman\" for her exploratory work in dozens of deadly bat SARS-coronaviruses. <ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-chinas-bat-woman-hunted-down-viruses-from-sars-to-the-new-coronavirus1/?amp=true | title=How China\u2019s \u201cBat Woman\u201d Hunted Down Viruses from SARS to the New Coronavirus | website=[[Scientific American]] | author1=Jane Qiu | date=11 March 2020}}</ref> She is a researcher at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV), which is part of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] (CAS). Shi and her colleague Cui Jie found that the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] virus originated in [[bat]]s.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Yang Wanli |title=Scientists close in on origin of SARS |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201712/07/WS5a288e90a310fcb6fafd2a17.html |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=Chinadaily |date=7 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207072350/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201712/07/WS5a288e90a310fcb6fafd2a17.html |archive-date=7 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://news.163.com/07/0525/17/3FBT6UN80001124J.html |script-title=zh:\u4e00\u4f4d\u5973\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u7684\u98ce\u91c7\u2014\u2014\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u535a\u58eb |work=163.com |date=2007-05-25 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015506/http://news.163.com/07/0525/17/3FBT6UN80001124J.html |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Shi is a member of the Virology Committee of the Chinese Society for Microbiology. She is an editor of the Board of ''Virologica Sinica'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Editorial Board |url=https://www.virosin.org/news/EditorialBoard.htm |website=Virologica Sinica |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> the ''Chinese Journal of Virology'', and the ''Journal of Fishery Sciences of China''.\n\n==Early life==\nShi was born in May 1964 in [[Xixia County]], [[Henan]], China.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |script-title=zh:\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\uff1a\u4e0e\u75c5\u6bd2\u76f8\u4f34\u7684\u5973\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6 |work=sciencenet.cn |date=2009-03-10 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020202/http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> She graduated from [[Wuhan University]] in 1987. She received her master's degree from the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]], [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] (CAS) in 1990 and her Ph.D. from [[Montpellier 2 University]] in France in 2000. \n\n==Research==\nIn 2005, a team led by Shi Zhengli and Cui Jie found that the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] virus originated in [[bat]]s.<ref>{{cite news |author1=David Cyranoski |title=Bat cave solves mystery of deadly SARS virus \u2014 and suggests new outbreak could occur |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-017-07766-9 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |work=nature.com |date=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117043400/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-017-07766-9 |archive-date=17 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The results were published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' in 2005<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Wendong |last2=Shi |first2=Zhengli |last3=Yu |first3=Meng |last4=Ren |first4=Wuze |last5=Smith |first5=Craig |last6=Epstein |first6=Jonathan H |last7=Wang |first7=Hanzhong |last8=Crameri |first8=Gary |last9=Hu |first9=Zhihong |last10=Zhang |first10=Huajun |last11=Zhang |first11=Jianhong |last12=McEachern |first12=Jennifer |last13=Field |first13=Hume |last14=Daszak |first14=Peter |last15=Eaton |first15=Bryan T |last16=Zhang |first16=Shuyi |last17=Wang |first17=Lin-Fa |title=Bats Are Natural Reservoirs of SARS-Like Coronaviruses |journal=Science |date=28 Oct 2005 |volume=310 |issue=5748 |pages=676\u2013679 |doi=10.1126/science.1118391 |pmid=16195424 |bibcode=2005Sci...310..676L }}</ref> and ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'' in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Lu Wei ({{lang|zh|\u9c81\u4f1f}}) |author2=Liu Zheng ({{lang|zh|\u5218\u94ee}}) |url=http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |script-title=zh:\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\uff1a\u4e0e\u75c5\u6bd2\u76f8\u4f34\u7684\u5973\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6 |work=sciencenet.cn |date=10 March 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020202/http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |archive-date=7 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ren |first1=Wuze |last2=Li |first2=Wendong |last3=Yu |first3=Meng |last4=Hao |first4=Pei |last5=Zhang |first5=Yuan |last6=Zhou |first6=Peng |last7=Zhang |first7=Shuyi |last8=Zhao |first8=Guoping |last9=Zhong |first9=Yang |last10=Wang |first10=Shengyue |last11=Wang |first11=Lin-Fa |last12=Shi |first12=Zhengli |title=Full-length genome sequences of two SARS-like coronaviruses in horseshoe bats and genetic variation analysis |journal=J Gen Virol |date=1 November 2006 |volume=87 |issue=11 |pages=3355\u20133359 |doi=10.1099/vir.0.82220-0 |pmid=17030870 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Shi Zhengli was involved in an investigation of bat coronaviruses, specifically gain of function experiments involving both the SARS and bat coronaviruses, a joint research of University of North Carolina and Wuhan Institute of Virology, with Ralph S. Baric as principal investigator.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Menachery|first=Vineet D.|last2=Yount|first2=Boyd L.|last3=Debbink|first3=Kari|last4=Agnihothram|first4=Sudhakar|last5=Gralinski|first5=Lisa E.|last6=Plante|first6=Jessica A.|last7=Graham|first7=Rachel L.|last8=Scobey|first8=Trevor|last9=Ge|first9=Xing-Yi|last10=Donaldson|first10=Eric F.|last11=Randell|first11=Scott H.|date=Nov 11, 2015|title=A SARS-like cluster of circulating bat coronaviruses shows potential for human emergence|journal=Nature Medicine|language=en|volume=21|issue=12|pages=1508\u20131513|doi=10.1038/nm.3985|pmid=26552008|pmc=4797993|issn=1546-170X}}</ref> That same year funding for the project in the US had been paused<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/sites/default/files/documents/43088final.pdf|title=Letters from NIH and NIAID telling 14 institutions to halt projects|last=Kaiser|first=Jocelyn|date=Nov 13, 2014|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> due to the moratorium on risky virology studies with influenza, MERS & SARS viruses, announced by the US government that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2014/11/moratorium-risky-virology-studies-leaves-work-14-institutions-limbo|title=Moratorium on risky virology studies leaves work at 14 institutions in limbo|last=Kaiser|first=Jocelyn|date=2014-11-17|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Shi and twelve other Institute scientists formed an expert group on the research of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2)]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Zhang Juan ({{lang|zh|\u5f20\u96bd}})|author2=Guan Xiyan ({{lang|zh|\u5173\u559c\u8273}})|url=http://hb.people.com.cn/n2/2020/0124/c194063-33743385.html |script-title=zh:\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u7b4913\u4f4d\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u961f \u653b\u5173\u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\u7814\u7a76 |work=people.com.cn |date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/01/mining-coronavirus-genomes-clues-outbreak-s-origins | title=Mining coronavirus genomes for clues to the outbreak's origins | magazine=[[Science (journal)|Science]] | author=Jon Cohen | date=1 February 2020 | accessdate=4 February 2020 | quote= team led by Shi Zheng-Li, a coronavirus specialist at the Wuhan Institute of Virology, reported on 23 January on bioRxiv that 2019-nCoV\u2019s sequence was 96.2% similar to a bat virus and had 79.5% similarity to the coronavirus that causes severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS), a disease whose initial outbreak was also in China more than 15 years ago.}}</ref>  In February 2020, researchers led by Shi Zhengli published an article in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' titled \"A pneumonia outbreak associated with a new coronavirus of probable bat origin\",<ref>{{cite journal | title=A pneumonia outbreak associated with a new coronavirus of probable bat origin | journal=[[Nature (journal) | Nature]] | author1=Shi Zhengli | author2=Team of 29 researchers at the WIV | date=3 February 2020| volume=579 | issue=7798 | pages=270\u2013273 | doi=10.1038/s41586-020-2012-7 | pmid=32015507 | pmc=7095418 }}</ref> and in a post on [[bioRxiv]], said that the SARS-CoV 2 is in the same family as SARS and closest to one found in bats.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Discovery of a novel coronavirus associated with the recent pneumonia outbreak in humans and its potential bat origin |url=https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.01.22.914952v1 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |journal=bioRxiv |date=23 January 2020|doi=10.1101/2020.01.22.914952 |last1=Zhou |first1=Peng |last2=Yang |first2=Xing-Lou |last3=Wang |first3=Xian-Guang |last4=Hu |first4=Ben |last5=Zhang |first5=Lei |last6=Zhang |first6=Wei |last7=Si |first7=Hao-Rui |last8=Zhu |first8=Yan |last9=Li |first9=Bei |last10=Huang |first10=Chao-Lin |last11=Chen |first11=Hui-Dong |last12=Chen |first12=Jing |last13=Luo |first13=Yun |last14=Guo |first14=Hua |last15=Jiang |first15=Ren-Di |last16=Liu |first16=Mei-Qin |last17=Chen |first17=Ying |last18=Shen |first18=Xu-Rui |last19=Wang |first19=Xi |last20=Zheng |first20=Xiao-Shuang |last21=Zhao |first21=Kai |last22=Chen |first22=Quan-Jiao |last23=Deng |first23=Fei |last24=Liu |first24=Lin-Lin |last25=Yan |first25=Bing |last26=Zhan |first26=Fa-Xian |last27=Wang |first27=Yan-Yi |last28=Xiao |first28=Geng-Fu |last29=Shi |first29=Zheng-Li |pages=2020.01.22.914952 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Antonio Regalado |title=Virus in Chinese outbreak is closest to one from bats, not snakes |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/f/615087/virus-in-chinese-outbreak-is-closest-to-one-from-bats-not-snakes/ |accessdate=26 January 2020 |work=technologyreview |date=23 January 2020}}</ref>  In February 2020, her team published a paper in ''[[Cell Research]]'' showing that [[remdesivir]], an experimental drug owned by [[Gilead Sciences]], had a positive effect in inhibiting the virus [[in vitro]], and applied for a patent for the drug in China on behalf of the WIV.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Remdesivir and chloroquine effectively inhibit the recently emerged novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) in vitro | date=4 February 2020 | journal=[[Cell Research]] | author1=Shi Zhengli | author2=Team of 10 researchers at the WIV| volume=30 | issue=3 | pages=269\u2013271 | doi=10.1038/s41422-020-0282-0 | pmid=32020029 | pmc=7054408 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-05/china-is-trying-to-patent-gilead-s-experimental-coronavirus-drug|title=China Wants to Patent Gilead's Experimental Coronavirus Drug|website=[[Bloomberg News]] |access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-treatments.html | title=China Begins Testing an Antiviral Drug in Coronavirus Patients | author=Denise Grady | newspaper=[[New York Times]] | date=6 February 2020 | accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>  Shi co-authored a paper labelling the virus as the first [[Disease X]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=The First Disease X is Caused by a Highly Transmissible Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus. | author1=Shi Zhengli | author2=Jiang Shibo | doi=10.1007/s12250-020-00206-5 | journal=Virologica Sinica |year = 2020|pmid = 32060789}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' reported that Shi's decade-long work to build up one of the world's largest databases of bat-related viruses gave the scientific community a \"head start\" in understanding the virus.<ref name=SCMP/>  The ''SCMP'' also reported that Shi was the focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media who claimed the WIV was the source of the virus, leading Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\", and when asked by the ''SCMP'' to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=SCMP>{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | author=Stephen Chen | date=6 February 2020 | accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>  ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | author1=Yang Rui | author2=Feng Yuding | author3=Zhao Jinchao | author4=Matthew Walsh | date=7 February 2020 | accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> Despite adamant denials and prior attacks, in a later interview conducted by ''Scientific American'' in March, she stated she remember[ed] thinking, \u201ccould they have come from our lab?\" when first informed of the outbreak due to its relatively unusual location.<ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-chinas-bat-woman-hunted-down-viruses-from-sars-to-the-new-coronavirus1/?amp=true | title=How China\u2019s \u201cBat Woman\u201d Hunted Down Viruses from SARS to the New Coronavirus | website=[[Scientific American]] | author1=Jane Qiu | date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter interviewing Shi, journalist Gao Yu said \"We learned later her institute finished gene-sequencing and related tests as early as January 2 but was muzzled.\" Shi said that Yanyi Wang, Director of the Wuhan Institute of Virology, had ordered staff not to disclose information on the disease arguing that 'inappropriate and inaccurate information was causing 'general panic'. Furthermore, Wang directed that \"The National Health Commission 'unequivocally requires that any tests, clinical data, test results, conclusions related to the epidemic shall not be posted on social media platforms, nor shall [it] be disclosed to any media outlets including government official media, nor shall [it] be disclosed to partner institutions,'\".<ref>[https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1268321/Coronavirus-Bat-Woman-findings-suppressed-China]</ref><ref>[https://www.ibtimes.sg/who-shi-zhengli-chinese-virologist-was-silenced-after-she-decoded-coronavirus-strain-december-42878]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* 2016 Chevalier of the [[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques]]<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6cd5\u56fd\u9a7b\u534e\u5927\u4f7f\u4eb2\u4e34\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u6240\u4e3a\u8881\u5fd7\u660e\u3001\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u7814\u7a76\u5458\u6388\u52cb |url=http://www.whiov.cas.cn/xwdt_160278/tpxw_160279/201911/t20191103_5419696.html |date=2016-06-20|publisher=Wuhan Institute of Virology|language=zh}}</ref>\n* 2018 State Natural Science Award (Second Class)<ref>{{cite news|author1=Huang Haihua ({{lang|zh|\u9ec4\u6d77\u534e}})|url=https://tech.sina.com.cn/roll/2020-01-24/doc-iihnzahk6109929.shtml |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u53ef\u80fd\u6765\u6e90\u4e8e\u8759\u8760\uff01\u201c\u8759\u8760\u5973\u4fa0\u201d\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u53d1\u73b0\u5176\u4e0e\u8759\u8760\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u540c\u6e90\u6027\u4e3a96% |work=sina |date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n* February 2019 Fellow of the [[American Academy of Microbiology]] (AAM)<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://www.xincailiao.com/news/news_detail.aspx?id=416531 |script-title=zh:\u5b66\u754c\u5927\u725b\uff0112\u4f4d\u534e\u4eba\u5b66\u8005\u5f53\u90092019\u5e74\u7f8e\u56fd\u5fae\u751f\u7269\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u9662\u58eb |work=xincailiao.com |date=2019-02-03 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015138/http://www.xincailiao.com/news/news_detail.aspx?id=416531 |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.ws-virology.org/dt_team/zhengli-shi/ Profile: Shi Zhengli], from the ''World Society of Virology''\n* [http://gd.whiov.cas.cn/dsjs/bssdsjj/201410/t20141013_261920.html Profile: Shi Zhengli], from the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shi, Zhengli}}\n\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques]]\n[[Category:Chinese virologists]]\n[[Category:Chinese women biologists]]\n[[Category:Biologists from Henan]]\n[[Category:Montpellier 2 University alumni]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China science writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Nanyang, Henan]]\n[[Category:Wuhan University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese researcher at the Wuhan Institute of Virology}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Shi (surname)|Shi]]}} \n{{Infobox scientist\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| name        = Shi Zhenglii\n| other_names = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1964|05|26}} \n| birth_place = [[Xixia County]], [[Henan]], China\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|}} or {{Death year and age| }}-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| residence   = \n| fields      = [[Virology]]\n| workplaces  = [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]]<br/> [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] (CAS)\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Wuhan University]]<br/>[[Wuhan Institute of Virology]]<br>[[Montpellier 2 University]]\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| awards      = \n| thesis_title =  <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =  <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =  <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =  <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| signature   =  <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =  <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes   = \n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u77f3|\u6b63|\u4e3d}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u77f3|\u6b63|\u9e97}}\n|p = Sh\u00ed Zh\u00e8ngl\u00ec \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n'''Shi Zhengli''' ({{zh|s=\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d|t=\u77f3\u6b63\u9e97}}; born 26 May 1964) is a Chinese [[virologist]] who has been dubbed \"bat woman\" for her exploratory work in dozens of deadly bat SARS-coronaviruses. <ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-chinas-bat-woman-hunted-down-viruses-from-sars-to-the-new-coronavirus1/?amp=true | title=How China\u2019s \u201cBat Woman\u201d Hunted Down Viruses from SARS to the New Coronavirus | website=[[Scientific American]] | author1=Jane Qiu | date=11 March 2020}}</ref> She is a researcher at the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] (WIV), which is part of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] (CAS). Shi and her colleague Cui Jie found that the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] virus originated in [[bat]]s.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Yang Wanli |title=Scientists close in on origin of SARS |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201712/07/WS5a288e90a310fcb6fafd2a17.html |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=Chinadaily |date=7 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207072350/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201712/07/WS5a288e90a310fcb6fafd2a17.html |archive-date=7 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://news.163.com/07/0525/17/3FBT6UN80001124J.html |script-title=zh:\u4e00\u4f4d\u5973\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6\u7684\u98ce\u91c7\u2014\u2014\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u7814\u7a76\u6240\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u535a\u58eb |work=163.com |date=2007-05-25 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015506/http://news.163.com/07/0525/17/3FBT6UN80001124J.html |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Shi is a member of the Virology Committee of the Chinese Society for Microbiology. She is an editor of the Board of ''Virologica Sinica'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Editorial Board |url=https://www.virosin.org/news/EditorialBoard.htm |website=Virologica Sinica |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> the ''Chinese Journal of Virology'', and the ''Journal of Fishery Sciences of China''.\n\n==Early life==\nShi was born in May 1964 in [[Xixia County]], [[Henan]], China.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |script-title=zh:\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\uff1a\u4e0e\u75c5\u6bd2\u76f8\u4f34\u7684\u5973\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6 |work=sciencenet.cn |date=2009-03-10 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020202/http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> She graduated from [[Wuhan University]] in 1987. She received her master's degree from the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]], [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] (CAS) in 1990 and her Ph.D. from [[Montpellier 2 University]] in France in 2000. \n\n==Research==\nIn 2005, a team led by Shi Zhengli and Cui Jie found that the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] virus originated in [[bat]]s.<ref>{{cite news |author1=David Cyranoski |title=Bat cave solves mystery of deadly SARS virus \u2014 and suggests new outbreak could occur |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-017-07766-9 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |work=nature.com |date=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117043400/https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-017-07766-9 |archive-date=17 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The results were published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' in 2005<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Wendong |last2=Shi |first2=Zhengli |last3=Yu |first3=Meng |last4=Ren |first4=Wuze |last5=Smith |first5=Craig |last6=Epstein |first6=Jonathan H |last7=Wang |first7=Hanzhong |last8=Crameri |first8=Gary |last9=Hu |first9=Zhihong |last10=Zhang |first10=Huajun |last11=Zhang |first11=Jianhong |last12=McEachern |first12=Jennifer |last13=Field |first13=Hume |last14=Daszak |first14=Peter |last15=Eaton |first15=Bryan T |last16=Zhang |first16=Shuyi |last17=Wang |first17=Lin-Fa |title=Bats Are Natural Reservoirs of SARS-Like Coronaviruses |journal=Science |date=28 Oct 2005 |volume=310 |issue=5748 |pages=676\u2013679 |doi=10.1126/science.1118391 |pmid=16195424 |bibcode=2005Sci...310..676L }}</ref> and ''[[Journal of General Virology]]'' in 2006.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Lu Wei ({{lang|zh|\u9c81\u4f1f}}) |author2=Liu Zheng ({{lang|zh|\u5218\u94ee}}) |url=http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |script-title=zh:\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\uff1a\u4e0e\u75c5\u6bd2\u76f8\u4f34\u7684\u5973\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6 |work=sciencenet.cn |date=10 March 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020202/http://news.sciencenet.cn/sbhtmlnews/2009/3/216816.html |archive-date=7 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ren |first1=Wuze |last2=Li |first2=Wendong |last3=Yu |first3=Meng |last4=Hao |first4=Pei |last5=Zhang |first5=Yuan |last6=Zhou |first6=Peng |last7=Zhang |first7=Shuyi |last8=Zhao |first8=Guoping |last9=Zhong |first9=Yang |last10=Wang |first10=Shengyue |last11=Wang |first11=Lin-Fa |last12=Shi |first12=Zhengli |title=Full-length genome sequences of two SARS-like coronaviruses in horseshoe bats and genetic variation analysis |journal=J Gen Virol |date=1 November 2006 |volume=87 |issue=11 |pages=3355\u20133359 |doi=10.1099/vir.0.82220-0 |pmid=17030870 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Shi Zhengli was involved in an investigation of bat coronaviruses, specifically gain of function experiments involving both the SARS and bat coronaviruses, a joint research of University of North Carolina and Wuhan Institute of Virology, with Ralph S. Baric as principal investigator.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Menachery|first=Vineet D.|last2=Yount|first2=Boyd L.|last3=Debbink|first3=Kari|last4=Agnihothram|first4=Sudhakar|last5=Gralinski|first5=Lisa E.|last6=Plante|first6=Jessica A.|last7=Graham|first7=Rachel L.|last8=Scobey|first8=Trevor|last9=Ge|first9=Xing-Yi|last10=Donaldson|first10=Eric F.|last11=Randell|first11=Scott H.|date=Nov 11, 2015|title=A SARS-like cluster of circulating bat coronaviruses shows potential for human emergence|journal=Nature Medicine|language=en|volume=21|issue=12|pages=1508\u20131513|doi=10.1038/nm.3985|pmid=26552008|pmc=4797993|issn=1546-170X}}</ref> That same year funding for the project in the US had been paused<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/sites/default/files/documents/43088final.pdf|title=Letters from NIH and NIAID telling 14 institutions to halt projects|last=Kaiser|first=Jocelyn|date=Nov 13, 2014|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> due to the moratorium on risky virology studies with influenza, MERS & SARS viruses, announced by the US government that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2014/11/moratorium-risky-virology-studies-leaves-work-14-institutions-limbo|title=Moratorium on risky virology studies leaves work at 14 institutions in limbo|last=Kaiser|first=Jocelyn|date=2014-11-17|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> \n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Shi and twelve other Institute scientists formed an expert group on the research of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2)]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Zhang Juan ({{lang|zh|\u5f20\u96bd}})|author2=Guan Xiyan ({{lang|zh|\u5173\u559c\u8273}})|url=http://hb.people.com.cn/n2/2020/0124/c194063-33743385.html |script-title=zh:\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u7b4913\u4f4d\u4e13\u5bb6\u7ec4\u961f \u653b\u5173\u65b0\u578b\u80ba\u708e\u7814\u7a76 |work=people.com.cn |date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/01/mining-coronavirus-genomes-clues-outbreak-s-origins | title=Mining coronavirus genomes for clues to the outbreak's origins | magazine=[[Science (journal)|Science]] | author=Jon Cohen | date=1 February 2020 | accessdate=4 February 2020 | quote= team led by Shi Zheng-Li, a coronavirus specialist at the Wuhan Institute of Virology, reported on 23 January on bioRxiv that 2019-nCoV\u2019s sequence was 96.2% similar to a bat virus and had 79.5% similarity to the coronavirus that causes severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS), a disease whose initial outbreak was also in China more than 15 years ago.}}</ref>  In February 2020, researchers led by Shi Zhengli published an article in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' titled \"A pneumonia outbreak associated with a new coronavirus of probable bat origin\",<ref>{{cite journal | title=A pneumonia outbreak associated with a new coronavirus of probable bat origin | journal=[[Nature (journal) | Nature]] | author1=Shi Zhengli | author2=Team of 29 researchers at the WIV | date=3 February 2020| volume=579 | issue=7798 | pages=270\u2013273 | doi=10.1038/s41586-020-2012-7 | pmid=32015507 | pmc=7095418 }}</ref> and in a post on [[bioRxiv]], said that the SARS-CoV 2 is in the same family as SARS and closest to one found in bats.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Discovery of a novel coronavirus associated with the recent pneumonia outbreak in humans and its potential bat origin |url=https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.01.22.914952v1 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |journal=bioRxiv |date=23 January 2020|doi=10.1101/2020.01.22.914952 |last1=Zhou |first1=Peng |last2=Yang |first2=Xing-Lou |last3=Wang |first3=Xian-Guang |last4=Hu |first4=Ben |last5=Zhang |first5=Lei |last6=Zhang |first6=Wei |last7=Si |first7=Hao-Rui |last8=Zhu |first8=Yan |last9=Li |first9=Bei |last10=Huang |first10=Chao-Lin |last11=Chen |first11=Hui-Dong |last12=Chen |first12=Jing |last13=Luo |first13=Yun |last14=Guo |first14=Hua |last15=Jiang |first15=Ren-Di |last16=Liu |first16=Mei-Qin |last17=Chen |first17=Ying |last18=Shen |first18=Xu-Rui |last19=Wang |first19=Xi |last20=Zheng |first20=Xiao-Shuang |last21=Zhao |first21=Kai |last22=Chen |first22=Quan-Jiao |last23=Deng |first23=Fei |last24=Liu |first24=Lin-Lin |last25=Yan |first25=Bing |last26=Zhan |first26=Fa-Xian |last27=Wang |first27=Yan-Yi |last28=Xiao |first28=Geng-Fu |last29=Shi |first29=Zheng-Li |pages=2020.01.22.914952 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Antonio Regalado |title=Virus in Chinese outbreak is closest to one from bats, not snakes |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/f/615087/virus-in-chinese-outbreak-is-closest-to-one-from-bats-not-snakes/ |accessdate=26 January 2020 |work=technologyreview |date=23 January 2020}}</ref>  In February 2020, her team published a paper in ''[[Cell Research]]'' showing that [[remdesivir]], an experimental drug owned by [[Gilead Sciences]], had a positive effect in inhibiting the virus [[in vitro]], and applied for a patent for the drug in China on behalf of the WIV.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Remdesivir and chloroquine effectively inhibit the recently emerged novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) in vitro | date=4 February 2020 | journal=[[Cell Research]] | author1=Shi Zhengli | author2=Team of 10 researchers at the WIV| volume=30 | issue=3 | pages=269\u2013271 | doi=10.1038/s41422-020-0282-0 | pmid=32020029 | pmc=7054408 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-05/china-is-trying-to-patent-gilead-s-experimental-coronavirus-drug|title=China Wants to Patent Gilead's Experimental Coronavirus Drug|website=[[Bloomberg News]] |access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/06/health/coronavirus-treatments.html | title=China Begins Testing an Antiviral Drug in Coronavirus Patients | author=Denise Grady | newspaper=[[New York Times]] | date=6 February 2020 | accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>  Shi co-authored a paper labelling the virus as the first [[Disease X]].<ref>{{cite journal | title=The First Disease X is Caused by a Highly Transmissible Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus. | author1=Shi Zhengli | author2=Jiang Shibo | doi=10.1007/s12250-020-00206-5 | journal=Virologica Sinica |year = 2020|pmid = 32060789}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' reported that Shi's decade-long work to build up one of the world's largest databases of bat-related viruses gave the scientific community a \"head start\" in understanding the virus.<ref name=SCMP/>  The ''SCMP'' also reported that Shi was the focus of personal attacks in Chinese social media who claimed the WIV was the source of the virus, leading Shi to post: \"I swear with my life, [the virus] has nothing to do with the lab\", and when asked by the ''SCMP'' to comment on the attacks, Shi responded: \"My time must be spent on more important matters\".<ref name=SCMP>{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3049397/bat-ladys-cave-exploits-offer-hope-beat-virus-sneakier-sars | title=Coronavirus: bat scientist's cave exploits offer hope to beat virus 'sneakier than Sars' | author=Stephen Chen | date=6 February 2020 | accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>  ''[[Caixin]]'' reported Shi made further public statements against \"perceived [[Tinfoil hat|tinfoil-hat]] theories about the new virus's source\", quoting her as saying: \"The novel 2019 coronavirus is nature punishing the human race for keeping uncivilized living habits. I, Shi Zhengli, swear on my life that it has nothing to do with our laboratory\".<ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-02-07/wuhan-virology-lab-deputy-director-again-slams-coronavirus-conspiracies-101512828.html | title=Wuhan Virology Lab Deputy Director Again Slams Coronavirus Conspiracies | website=[[Caixin]] | author1=Yang Rui | author2=Feng Yuding | author3=Zhao Jinchao | author4=Matthew Walsh | date=7 February 2020 | accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref> Despite adamant denials and prior attacks, in a later interview conducted by Scientific American in March, she stated she remember[ed] thinking, \u201ccould they have come from our lab?\" when first informed of the outbreak due to its relatively unusual location. <ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-chinas-bat-woman-hunted-down-viruses-from-sars-to-the-new-coronavirus1/?amp=true | title=How China\u2019s \u201cBat Woman\u201d Hunted Down Viruses from SARS to the New Coronavirus | website=[[Scientific American]] | author1=Jane Qiu | date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter interviewing Shi, journalist Gao Yu said \"We learned later her institute finished gene-sequencing and related tests as early as January 2 but was muzzled.\" Shi said that Yanyi Wang, Director of the Wuhan Institute of Virology, had ordered staff not to disclose information on the disease arguing that 'inappropriate and inaccurate information was causing 'general panic'. Furthermore, Wang directed that \"The National Health Commission 'unequivocally requires that any tests, clinical data, test results, conclusions related to the epidemic shall not be posted on social media platforms, nor shall [it] be disclosed to any media outlets including government official media, nor shall [it] be disclosed to partner institutions,'\".<ref>[https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1268321/Coronavirus-Bat-Woman-findings-suppressed-China]</ref><ref>[https://www.ibtimes.sg/who-shi-zhengli-chinese-virologist-was-silenced-after-she-decoded-coronavirus-strain-december-42878]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* 2016 Chevalier of the [[Ordre des Palmes acad\u00e9miques]]<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6cd5\u56fd\u9a7b\u534e\u5927\u4f7f\u4eb2\u4e34\u6b66\u6c49\u75c5\u6bd2\u6240\u4e3a\u8881\u5fd7\u660e\u3001\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u7814\u7a76\u5458\u6388\u52cb |url=http://www.whiov.cas.cn/xwdt_160278/tpxw_160279/201911/t20191103_5419696.html |date=2016-06-20|publisher=Wuhan Institute of Virology|language=zh}}</ref>\n* 2018 State Natural Science Award (Second Class)<ref>{{cite news|author1=Huang Haihua ({{lang|zh|\u9ec4\u6d77\u534e}})|url=https://tech.sina.com.cn/roll/2020-01-24/doc-iihnzahk6109929.shtml |script-title=zh:\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u53ef\u80fd\u6765\u6e90\u4e8e\u8759\u8760\uff01\u201c\u8759\u8760\u5973\u4fa0\u201d\u77f3\u6b63\u4e3d\u53d1\u73b0\u5176\u4e0e\u8759\u8760\u51a0\u72b6\u75c5\u6bd2\u540c\u6e90\u6027\u4e3a96% |work=sina |date=24 January 2020 |accessdate=26 January 2020 |language=zh}}</ref>\n* February 2019 Fellow of the [[American Academy of Microbiology]] (AAM)<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://www.xincailiao.com/news/news_detail.aspx?id=416531 |script-title=zh:\u5b66\u754c\u5927\u725b\uff0112\u4f4d\u534e\u4eba\u5b66\u8005\u5f53\u90092019\u5e74\u7f8e\u56fd\u5fae\u751f\u7269\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u9662\u58eb |work=xincailiao.com |date=2019-02-03 |language=zh |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207015138/http://www.xincailiao.com/news/news_detail.aspx?id=416531 |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.ws-virology.org/dt_team/zhengli-shi/ Profile: Shi Zhengli], from the ''World Society of Virology''\n* [http://gd.whiov.cas.cn/dsjs/bssdsjj/201410/t20141013_261920.html Profile: Shi Zhengli], from the [[Wuhan Institute of Virology]] {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shi, Zhengli}}\n\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques]]\n[[Category:Chinese virologists]]\n[[Category:Chinese women biologists]]\n[[Category:Biologists from Henan]]\n[[Category:Montpellier 2 University alumni]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China science writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Nanyang, Henan]]\n[[Category:Wuhan University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Art LaPella", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResearch:Italics. Remove a space.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shi_Zhengli"}
{"title_page": "Alexandra Daddario", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Alexandra Daddario\n| image        = Alexandra Daddario April 2015.jpg\n| caption      = Daddario at [[WonderCon]] in April 2015\n| birth_name   = Alexandra Anna Daddario\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1986|3|16|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1998\u2013present\n| relatives    = {{ubl|[[Matthew Daddario]] (brother)|[[Emilio Q. Daddario]] (grandfather)}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexandra Anna Daddario''' (born March 16, 1986) is an American actress. She is known for playing Annabeth Chase in the [[Percy Jackson (film series)|''Percy Jackson'' film series]], Blake Gaines in ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]'' (2015), [[Summer Quinn]] in ''[[Baywatch (film)|Baywatch]]'' (2017), and Emma Corrigan in ''[[Can You Keep a Secret? (film)|Can You Keep a Secret?]]'' (2019). She has also starred in the films ''[[Texas Chainsaw 3D]]'' and ''[[Hall Pass]]'' and has guest starred in television series such as ''[[White Collar (TV series)|White Collar]]'', ''[[It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia]]'', ''[[True Detective]]'', ''[[New Girl]]'', and ''[[American Horror Story: Hotel]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nAlexandra Anna Daddario<ref name=\"MiddleName\">{{cite tweet |number=11500480268 |title=Alexandra Daddario tweet |user=AADaddario |author=Alexandra Daddario |date=April 3, 2010}}</ref> was born in [[New York City]] on March 16, 1986,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/alexandra-daddario-57543389/ |title=Alexandra Daddario |website=Hollywood.com |accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref> the eldest child of Christina, a lawyer and [[Richard Daddario]], a prosecutor and former head of the [[New York City Police Department]] counter-terrorism unit under Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]].<ref name=\"VanityFairBikini\">{{cite web |last=Rao |first=Priya |title=The Case of the Missing Bikini |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/04/alexandra-daddario-true-detective|access-date=March 3, 2015 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=April 10, 2014}}</ref> She is of Italian, Irish, English and Slovak/Hungarian descent.<ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Woodhall |url=http://www.thegentlemansjournal.com/woman-week-alexandra-daddario/ |title=Woman Of The Week: Alexandra Daddario |publisher=The Gentleman's Journal |date=February 19, 2014 |accessdate=February 11, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160221222428/http://www.thegentlemansjournal.com/woman-week-alexandra-daddario/ |archivedate=February 21, 2016}}</ref> Her brother, [[Matthew Daddario]], is also an actor,<ref name=\"Brother\">{{cite web |last=Sneider |first=Jeff |url=https://variety.com/2011/film/news/matthew-daddario-joins-doremus-pic-1118041399 |title=Matthew Daddario joins Doremus pic |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=August 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dustin |last=Rawls |url=http://www.pajiba.com/celebrities_are_better_than_you/fyi-apparently-alexandra-daddario-and-her-siblings-got-first-pick-at-the-gene-pool-draft.php |title=FYI: Apparently Alexandra Daddario and Her Siblings Got First Pick at the Gene Pool Draft |website=Pajiba |date=January 29, 2014 |accessdate=February 11, 2016}}</ref> and she has a sister named Catharine.<ref name=\"GQ2014\">{{cite web |title=How to Date Me |url=https://thescene.com/watch/gq/how-to-date-alexandra-daddario |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |work=[[GQ]] |date=December 1, 2014}}</ref> Her paternal grandfather was [[Emilio Q. Daddario]], a Democratic member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] for [[Connecticut]] from 1959 to 1971.<ref name=\"Grandfather\">{{cite web |title=Emilio Daddario, Connecticut Congressman, Dies at 91 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/08/nyregion/08daddario.html |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDaddario was raised on [[Manhattan]]'s [[Upper East Side]]. She attended [[Brearley School]] as well as the [[Professional Children's School]].<ref name=\"OrangeCounty2010\">{{cite web |last=Berrie |first=Nicole |title=The Radar: Alexandra Daddario |url=http://orangecounty.modernluxury.com/style/radar-alexandra-daddario |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |website=Orange County |date=February 8, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613012155/http://orangecounty.modernluxury.com/style/radar-alexandra-daddario|archive-date=June 13, 2010}}</ref> Daddario said she decided to be an actress at the age of eleven.<ref name=\"ViewLondon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/cinemas/alexandra-daddario-interview-feature-3633.html |title=Alexandra Daddario Interview |last=Turner |first=Matthew |website=View London |date=2010 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> \"I always loved storytelling,\" she stated in 2019. \"It was just something I genuinely wanted to do\u2014and I could've done anything, really. I did have every opportunity on the planet.\"<ref>{{cite interview |work=Whiskey Ginger Podcast |title=Alexandra Daddario - #014 |date=January 25, 2019 |time=36:55 |via=YouTube |last=Daddario |first=Alexandra |interviewer=Andrew Santino |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W1W0dYog3w0}}</ref> She attended [[Marymount Manhattan College]] before dropping out to pursue acting full-time.<ref name=\"DailyBeast2014\">{{cite web |last=Stern |first=Marlow |title=Alexandra Daddario on 'True Detective's' Misogyny Claims and Her Hollywood Ascent |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/09/05/alexandra-daddario-on-true-detective-s-misogyny-claims-and-her-hollywood-ascent.html |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=September 5, 2014 |accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref> She has studied the [[Meisner technique|Meisner acting technique]] for years.<ref name=\"InterviewMag\">{{cite web |last=Wallace |first=Chris |title=Alexandra Daddario |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/alexandra-daddario |website=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |date=June 2014 |accessdate=March 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDaddario made her television debut at the age of 16, when she played victimized teen Laurie Lewis in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] daytime soap opera ''[[All My Children]]''. Her first major role was as [[List of characters in mythology novels by Rick Riordan#Annabeth Chase|Annabeth Chase]] in the fantasy adventure film ''[[Percy Jackson & the Olympians: The Lightning Thief]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/53817-alexandra-daddario-joining-percy-jackson |title=Up And Comer Alexandra Daddario Joining Percy Jackson |website=[[ComingSoon.net]] |date=March 19, 2009}}</ref> She also had a recurring role as Neal Caffrey's love interest [[Kate Moreau]] in the [[USA Network]]'s procedural drama series ''[[White Collar (TV series)|White Collar]]''. In 2011, she co-starred in ''[[Hall Pass]]'' and had a recurring role as Rachel in [[NBC]]'s comedy-drama series ''[[Parenthood (2010 TV series)|Parenthood]]''.<ref name=\"Parenthood\">{{cite web |last=Masters |first=Megan |title=Parenthood Exclusive: White Collar Alum Alexandra Daddario Joins the Family Biz |url=http://tvline.com/2011/09/21/parenthood-casting-alexandra-daddario/ |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |website=[[TVLine]] |date=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Daddario starred in the music video for [[Imagine Dragons]]' song \"[[Radioactive (Imagine Dragons song)|Radioactive]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2015/05/30/alexandra-daddario-facts-san-andreas-true-detective/ |title=Alexandra Daddario: 5 Things To Know About The Sexy 'San Andreas' Star |accessdate=February 12, 2019 |date=May 30, 2015 |work=[[Hollywood Life]] |author=Fuller, Bonnie}}</ref> and she had an episode guest stint in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] sitcom ''[[It's Always Sunny in Philadelphia]]'' as Ruby Taft. Her first starring role after ''Percy Jackson'' was the slasher film ''[[Texas Chainsaw 3D]]'' (2013) as the lead character Heather Miller. In the latter part of 2013, Daddario reprised her role as Annabeth Chase in the film sequel ''[[Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters]]''. She then appeared in the romantic horror comedy ''[[Burying the Ex]]'' with [[Anton Yelchin]] and [[Ashley Greene]]. ''Burying the Ex'' was among the chosen films participating but not competing at the [[Venice Film Festival]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lodge |first=Guy |title=Venice Film Review: 'Burying the Ex' |date=September 4, 2014 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/festivals/venice-film-review-burying-the-ex-1201297573/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407214122/http://variety.com/2014/film/festivals/venice-film-review-burying-the-ex-1201297573/ |archivedate=April 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Alexandra Daddario 2016.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Daddario at [[Austin Film Festival]] in October 2016]]\nOn January 2013, Daddario was cast in the first season of the [[HBO]] anthology series ''[[True Detective]]''.<ref name=\"VanityFairTrueDetective\">{{cite web |last=Rao |first=Priya |title=Alexandra Daddario Talks True Detective, Boobs, and Fashion |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/02/alexandra-daddario |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=February 22, 2014}}</ref> She appeared in a four-episode arc as Lisa Tragnetti, a court reporter having an extramarital affair with [[Woody Harrelson]]'s character. Her scenes, which included nudity, attracted much attention.<ref name=\"MTVTrueDetective\">{{cite web |last=Sullivan |first=Kevin P. |title=Alexandra Daddario Talks 'True Detective' Nude Scene: 'I Just Sort Of Did It' |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1720728/alexandra-daddario-true-detective-nude-scenes/ |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |website=[[MTV News]] |date=January 17, 2014}}</ref> The following year, she had a lead role as Blake Gaines in the disaster film ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]'', alongside [[Dwayne Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2014/02/up-and-comer-alexandra-daddario-lands-san-andreas-lead-opposite-the-rock-676993/ |title=Up And Comer Alexandra Daddario Lands 'San Andreas' Lead Opposite The Rock |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |last=Fleming Jr. |first=Mike |date=February 4, 2014 |accessdate=February 27, 2014}}</ref> Also in 2015, Daddario made a cameo appearance in the pilot of the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] comedy series ''[[The Last Man on Earth (TV series)|The Last Man on Earth]]'' created by and starring [[Will Forte]],<ref name=\"LastManOnEarth\">{{cite web |last=Framke |first=Caroline |title=The Last Man On Earth: \"Alive In Tucson\"/\"The Elephant In The Room\" |url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/last-man-earth-alive-tucson-elephant-room-215926 |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=March 1, 2015}}</ref> and the same year saw her guest appearance on ''[[American Horror Story: Hotel]]'', portraying a fictionalized version of designer [[Natacha Rambova]].<ref name=\"AHS\">{{cite web |last=Stephens |first=Emily L. |title=American Horror Story: Hotel does its best work without words |url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/american-horror-story-hotel-does-its-best-work-wit-228591 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 19, 2015 |accessdate=November 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the actress had a supporting role in the [[Nicholas Sparks]] romantic drama film ''[[The Choice (2016 film)|The Choice]]'', directed by [[Ross Katz]].<ref name=\"TheChoice\">{{cite web |last=Sneider |first=Jeff |title='True Detective' actress Alexandra Daddario Joins Nicholas Sparks Adaptation 'The Choice' |url=http://www.thewrap.com/true-detectives-alexandra-daddario-joins-nicholas-sparks-adaptation-the-choice |accessdate=March 3, 2015 |website=[[TheWrap]] |date=October 8, 2014}}</ref> Daddario subsequently starred as one of the leads in the [[Baywatch (film)|film adaptation of ''Baywatch'']] (2017), reuniting with her ''San Andreas'' co-star Dwayne Johnson. She played Summer Quinn, who was portrayed by [[Nicole Eggert]] in the original television series.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike |title=Alexandra Daddario Lands 'Baywatch' Female Lead |url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/alexandra-daddario-baywatch-movie-true-detective-dwayne-johnson-zac-efron-1201627862/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 18, 2015}}</ref> That same year, Daddario portrayed Kate Jeffries, alongside [[Kate Upton]], in the road trip comedy ''[[The Layover (film)|The Layover]]'' (2017), directed by [[William H. Macy]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |title=Tim Griffin Joins 'Central Intelligence'; Alexandra Daddario In For 'The Layover' |url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/alexandra-daddario-the-layover-movie-kate-upton-william-h-macy-1201422603/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 7, 2015}}</ref> In 2018, Daddario appeared in the music video \"[[Wait (Maroon 5 song)|Wait]]\" by [[Maroon 5]] and starred as Avery Martin in the romantic comedy ''[[When We First Met]]'', opposite the film's co-writer [[Adam DeVine]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Pedersen |first=Erik |title=Adam Devine & Alexandra Daddario Will Reminisce About 'When We First Met' |url=http://deadline.com/2016/05/adam-devine-alexandra-daddario-when-first-we-met-ari-sandel-1201750999/ |accessdate=July 20, 2016 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=May 6, 2016}}</ref> Daddario also appeared as a Scuba Diver in ''[[Rampage (2018 film)|Rampage]]'' directed by [[Brad Peyton]] but was cut in the final film.<ref name=\"Rampage\">{{cite web |title=Rampage Deleted Scene \u2013 Alexandra Daddario Cameo (2018) |url=https://cypriumnews.com/rampage-deleted-scene-alexandra-daddario-cameo-2018-sci-fi-action-movie/ |work=Cypriumnews |date=July 26, 2018 |accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=October 2019}} Daddario starred as Constance Blackwood in ''[[We Have Always Lived in the Castle (film)|We Have Always Lived in the Castle]]'', a [[Stacie Passon]]-directed film adaptation of [[Shirley Jackson]]'s mystery thriller novel of the same name.<ref name=\"Castle\">{{cite web |first=Borys |last=Kit |title=Alexandra Daddario, Taissa Farmiga Join Sebastian Stan in 'We Have Always Lived in the Castle' |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alexandra-daddario-taissa-farmiga-join-918692 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 10, 2016}}</ref> Daddario has been cast alongside [[Henry Cavill]] and Sir [[Ben Kingsley]] in the psychological thriller ''[[Night Hunter (2018 film)|Night Hunter]]'' (originally titled ''Nomis''),<ref name=\"Nomis\">{{cite web |first=Ashley |last=Lee |title=Berlin: Ben Kingsley, Henry Cavill to Star in Psychological Thriller 'Nomis' |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/berlin-ben-kingsley-henry-cavill-star-psychological-thriller-nomis-974061 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> and is also headlining the drama-thriller film ''Lost Girls and Love Hotels''.<ref name=\"Bird\">{{cite web |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |title=Alexandra Daddario To Star In 'I Am Not a Bird' Thriller From Director William Olsson |url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/alexandra-daddario-i-am-not-a-bird-film-director-william-olsson-1202180469/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> Daddario starred in and acted as executive producer for the romantic comedy ''[[Can You Keep a Secret? (film)|Can You Keep a Secret?]]'', based on the [[Can You Keep a Secret? (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Sophie Kinsella]],<ref>{{cite web |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |title=Alexandra Daddario To Star & Executive Produce NY Times Bestseller 'Can You Keep a Secret?' |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/alexandra-daddario-to-star-executive-produce-ny-times-bestseller-can-you-keep-a-secret-1202432693/ |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 24, 2018}}</ref> and will be appearing in the film ''Happy Life''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://teendaily.net/2019/07/alexandra-daddario-to-star-in-happy-life/ |title=Alexandra Daddario to star in 'Happy Life' |work=Teen Daliy |accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| data-sort-value=\"Squid and the Whale, The\" | ''[[The Squid and the Whale]]''\n| Pretty girl\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2006\n| data-sort-value=\"Hottest State, The\" | ''[[The Hottest State]]''\n| Kim\n|\n|-\n| ''Pitch''\n| Alex\n| Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2007\n| data-sort-value=\"Attic, The\" | ''[[The Attic (2007 film)|The Attic]]''\n| Ava Strauss\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Babysitters, The\" | ''[[The Babysitters]]''\n| Barbara Yates\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2010\n| ''[[Bereavement (film)|Bereavement]]''\n| Allison Miller\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Percy Jackson & the Olympians: The Lightning Thief]]''\n|[[List of characters in mythology novels by Rick Riordan#Annabeth Chase|Annabeth Chase]]\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Hall Pass]]''\n| Paige\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2013\n| ''Life in Text''\n| Haley Greene\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''[[Percy Jackson: Sea of Monsters]]''\n| Annabeth Chase\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Texas Chainsaw 3D]]''\n| Heather Miller\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Burying the Ex]]''\n| Olivia\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| ''Faces Without Eyes''\n| Iris\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''[[San Andreas (film)|San Andreas]]''\n| Blake Gaines\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| ''Baked in Brooklyn''\n| Kate Winston\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Choice, The\" | ''[[The Choice (2016 film)|The Choice]]''\n| Monica\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2017\n| ''[[Baywatch (film)|Baywatch]]''\n| Summer Quinn\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"House, The\" | ''[[The House (2017 film)|The House]]''\n| Corsica\n| Deleted scene only \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Layover, The\" | ''[[The Layover (film)|The Layover]]''\