{"title_page": "2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries", "text_new": "{{short description|Series of electoral contests}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries\n| country = United States\n| type = primary\n| ongoing = yes\n| party_name = no\n| previous_year = [[2016 Libertarian Party presidential primaries|2016]]\n| election_date = January 11 to June 16, 2020\n| next_election = \n| next_year = ''2024''\n| votes_for_election = \n| image1 = [[File:Jacob Hornberger by Gage Skidmore (cropped) (2).jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate1 = [[:simple:Jacob Hornberger|Jacob Hornberger]]\n| color1 = DAA520\n| home_state1 = [[Virginia]]\n| states_carried1 = 6{{efn|No preference received the most votes in North Carolina. Hornberger, the candidate who had received the most votes, was not recognized as the winner.}}\n| popular_vote1 = 8,908\n| percentage1 = 22.02%\n\n| image2 = [[File:Vermin Supreme August 2019 (cropped).jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate2 = [[Vermin Supreme]]\n| color2 = fb9bc2\n| home_state2 = [[Massachusetts]]\n| states_carried2 = 2{{efn|No preference received the most votes in Massachusetts. Supreme, the candidate who had received the most votes, was recognized as the winner by the Secretary of State.}}\n| popular_vote2 = 4,047\n| percentage2 = 10.00%\n\n| image3 = [[File:2020_Libertarian_Party_presidential_candidate_Jo_Jorgensen.jpg|115px]]\n| candidate3 = [[Jo Jorgensen]]\n| color3 = BA55D3\n| home_state3 = [[South Carolina]]\n| states_carried3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 3,891\n| percentage3 = 9.62%\n\n| image4 = [[File:NOTA Option Logo.png|130px]]\n| candidate4 = [[None of the above|Uncommitted]]\n| color4 = 000000\n| states_carried4 = 1\n| popular_vote4 = 3,458\n| percentage4 = 8.55%\n\n| image5 = [[File:Ken Armstrong POTUS46 Headshot.jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate5 = Ken Armstrong\n| color5 = F0E68C\n| home_state5 = [[Oregon]]\n| states_carried5 = 0\n| popular_vote5 = 3,328\n| percentage5 = 8.23%\n\n| image6 = [[File:2020_Libertarian_Presidential_Candidate_Adam_Kokesh.jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate6 = [[Adam Kokesh]]\n| color6 = 32CD32\n| home_state6 = [[Arizona]]\n| states_carried6 = 0\n| popular_vote6 = 2,380\n| percentage6 = 5.88%\n\n| image7 = [[File:Dan-taxation-is-theft-behrman (cropped).jpg|x160px]]\n| candidate7 = Dan Behrman\n| color7 = ff7102\n| home_state7 = [[Texas]]\n| states_carried7 = 0\n| popular_vote7 = 2,080\n| percentage7 = 5.14%\n\n| title = Libertarian nominee\n| before_election = [[Gary Johnson]]\n| after_election = \n| map_image = Libertarian Party presidential primaries results, 2020.svg\n| map_size = 350px\n| map_caption = {{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{legend|#DAA520|Jacob Hornberger (6)|border=0}}\n{{legend|#fb9bc2|Vermin Supreme (2)|border=0}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{legend|#000000|Uncommitted (1)|border=0}}\n{{Col-end}}\n}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\n\nThe '''2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries and caucuses''' is a series of electoral contests to indicate non-binding preferences for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party's]] presidential candidate in the [[2020 United States presidential election]]. These differ from the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] or [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential primaries and caucuses in that they do not appoint delegates to represent a candidate at the party's convention to select the party's presidential nominee. The party's nominee will be chosen directly by registered delegates at the [[2020 Libertarian National Convention]] from May 21\u201325, 2020 in [[Austin, Texas]].\n\n== Background ==\nThe [[2020 United States Presidential election]] will be the thirteenth contested presidential election that the Libertarian Party will participate in. The [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election]] saw the highest vote total and percentage of votes for a Libertarian presidential ticket ever, with former [[Governor of New Mexico|New Mexico governor]] [[Gary Johnson]] and his [[running mate]], former [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts governor]] [[Bill Weld]], receiving over four million votes and 3.28% of the total vote. During [[Gary Johnson 2016 presidential campaign|his presidential campaign]] in 2016, Johnson often stated that it would be his last run for the presidency.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NFb5-T_0XIE |title=Gary Johnson on Running in 2020 & Aleppo |website=[[YouTube]] |date=October 20, 2016 |access-date=October 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Candidates ==\n=== Declared candidates ===\nThe following is a list of declared candidates who meet at least one of the following criteria: a) meet Wikipedia's  [[Notability in the English Wikipedia|notability guidelines]]; b) have participated (or have been invited to participate) in at least two Libertarian Party-sponsored debates or c) have received substantial media coverage.\n<!-- {{legend|lavender|Formed exploratory committee but has not officially declared candidacy}} -->\n<section begin=\"declared\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"padding:10px; width:120px; \" | Candidate\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Born\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:300px;\"  class=\"unsortable\" | Experience\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Home state\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Campaign\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"padding:10px;\" | Popular vote\n! rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Contests won\n! rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Ref\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Hornberger, Jacob\"|[[File:Jacob Hornberger by Gage Skidmore (cropped) (2).jpg|120px]]<br />'''[[:simple:Jacob Hornberger|Jacob Hornberger]]'''|| style=\"background:#DAA520;\" |\n|{{dts|1950|1|1}}<br /> (age {{age nts|1950|1|1}})<br />[[Laredo, Texas]]\n|'''Founder and President of the Future of Freedom Foundation'''<br />Independent candidate for [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] from [[Virginia]] in [[2002 United States Senate election in Virginia|2002]]<br />Candidate for President in [[2000 Libertarian National Convention|2000]]\n|[[File:Flag of Virginia.svg|73px|border]]<br />[[Virginia]]\n|{{Hs|2019-10-29}}[[File:Hornbergerlogo.png|100px]]<br />October 29, 2019<br />FEC Filing<ref>{{cite web |url=https://docquery.fec.gov/pdf/559/201910299165305559/201910299165305559.pdf |title=FEC FORM 2 : STATEMENT OF CANDIDACY |website=Docquery.fec.gov |access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| data-sort-value=\"8908\" | 8,908<br /><small>(22.02%)</small>\n|'''6'''<br />([[2020 United States presidential election in Iowa#Libertarian caucuses|IA]], MN, [[2020 United States presidential election in Missouri#Libertarian primary|MO]], NY, [[2020 United States presidential election in California#Libertarian primary|CA]], OH)\n|<ref name=\"CarolinaDebate\">{{cite web |url=https://reason.com/2019/11/07/candidates-vie-to-represent-the-libertarian-wing-of-the-libertarian-party/ |title=Candidates Vie to Represent the Libertarian Wing of the Libertarian Party |author=Welch, Matt |author-link=Matt Welch |date=November 7, 2019 |work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] |access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Supreme, Vermin\"|[[File:Vermin Supreme August 2019.jpg|120px]]<br />'''[[Vermin Supreme]]'''|| style=\"background:#fb9bc2;\" |\n| {{dts|1961|6|3}}<br />(age 58)<br />[[Rockport, Massachusetts]]\n| '''Performance artist and activist'''<br />[[Perennial candidate|Candidate]] for President in [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1992|1992]], [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1996|1996]], [[2000 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2000]], [[2004 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2004]], [[2008 Republican Party presidential primaries|2008]], [[2012 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2012]], and [[2016 Libertarian Party presidential primaries|2016]]<br />Candidate for [[List of mayors of Detroit|Mayor]] of [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]] in 1989<br />Candidate for [[List of 